statement.p:
				A 20\text{-}\mu\text{F} capacitor is connected across a 10\text{-V} AC source (i.e., V_\text{rms} = 10\text{ V}) of variable frequency f.  Find current amplitude in the circuit for the following values of f.  Assume negligible resistance.


  1.0 \text{ Hz} 

  10.0 \text{ Hz} 

  100.0 \text{ Hz} 

  1.0 \text{ kHz} 

  10.0 \text{ kHz} 

  100.0 \text{ kHz} 

  1.0 \text{ MHz}

  1.0 \text{ GHz}

solution.p:
				The amplitude of the current in the circuit will be given by

					I_0 = \dfrac{\sqrt{2}\:V_{\text{rms}}}{|Z|} = \sqrt{2}\:V_{\text{rms}}\times 2\pi\:f\:C.

				Using the values given in the problem we find the following for the frequency f Hz source.

					I_0 =  \sqrt{2}\:V_{\text{rms}}\times 2\pi\:f\:C = 1.777\: f\ \ [\text{units: mA}].



  1.77 \text{ mA} 

  17.7 \text{ mA} 

  178 \text{ mA} 

  1.78 \text{ A} 

  17.8 \text{ A} 

  178 \text{ A} 

  1.78 \text{ kA}

  1.78 \text{ MA}

Using I_0 = V_0/|Z| = V_0\omega C, we obtain


	 C \amp = \dfrac{I_0}{2\pi\:f\:V_0} 
	 \amp =  \dfrac{1.2\:\text{A}}{2\pi\:60\:\text{Hz}\times 170\: \text{V}} = 18.7\:\mu\text{F}.
